hi everyone anthony b tano here the
internet's busiest music nerd and it's
time for a review of this new yule album
glitch princess this is the newest
full-length lp from songwriter producer
and singer nat shamil aka yule out now
on bayonet records this is their second
album to date which builds on the airy
ambient pop textures of 2019's serotonin
2 and in addition to that offers a
glitchy and futuristic aesthetic that
also works as an exercise in world
building i don't see glitch princess
merely as an assembly of songs or tracks
but an attempt at crafting a persona and
a world for it to exist in and i find
this record doesn't just embody its
influences creatively in part it feels
like the next logical step past them
this is really a record for a post
pandemic post information age post
bedroom pop post gender post hyper pop
post pc music post fka twigs post sophie
world the whole thing sounds like sad
longing robot feelings that ai will no
doubt be fantasizing about once it gains
the ability to have dreams and that
point's pushed to where sometimes the
record i think is saying more
narratively than it is musically like on
the intro track my name is nat shamil
which is this slow glitchy spoken word
piece where nat states some personal
characteristics and preferences name
age loves their cat
drugs
dressing up sex essentially the
audiobook version of a surreal cyberpunk
dating profile the pacing is a little
tedious yes but the awkward speech
patterns eerie keys and
glitchy vocal effects do bring a point
home then there's also flowers are dead
which is another moment where i think
the concept trumps the music a little
bit the whaling tones and static lace
drones lay down a desolate digital
landscape the unsettling ambience of it
is kind of alluring though i don't
really get too much out of nat's breathy
vocal leads and and the overall lack of
development of the song however there
are plenty of other tracks on this
project that either stun with their
outright beauty or inspire wonder with
their interesting progressions and genre
combinations there's electric which
danny l harl's fingerprints are all over
danny is a pretty key co-producer on
many tracks here the heavy beats the
pristine atmosphere the beautiful vocal
work are all impressive on this one the
bursts of synths and lead melodies on
the second half of the track sound like
listening to the big bang then there's
eyes which a new age more like neo age
we have more intimate vocals on this one
crisp reverbs and the kind of sad simple
cinematic piano work you might catch in
a han zimmer piece plus i love the
winding road this track takes into a
heavy crushing post-industrial distorted
outro furthermore fragments harsh and
crushing walls of synthetic noise and
tones are incredible perfect blue
features an oddly satisfying and
beautiful attempt at a duet with two
vocals that both feature these somewhat
awkward and very robotic characteristics
and don't be so hard on your beauty
makes a refreshing change of pace with
an acoustic cut which given all of the
unlikely influences on the record so far
it's surprising how well this one goes
over so there are a lot of textured and
abstract highlights on this record that
i love but weirdly the songs that i
ended up wanting more from were the ones
that felt louder and more
straightforward two dead inside for
example is a breathy pop cut with some
of the uh darkest starkest and most
groovy production on the entire record
but the beats seriously lacking
something on the color side the texture
side i'm not exactly sold on this
awkward chorus either it's decent but
still sounds like something that could
have been off the last grimes lp i love
you seems inspired at least in part by
the very soft intimacy of recent hits
from pink panther s but something about
the magic of that feels lost in
translation as nap moves the song from
potentially a ballad to this semi-spoken
word piece with soaring post-rock
guitars and a lot of glitchy vocal
chatter so these many songs make up
pretty much the core record experience
but from here i'd like to transition
into the final moments of the album
namely the closer which if you can
believe it or not is an almost five-hour
long ambient piece built on these vocal
synth patches
that just kind of work through a very
long series of melodic resolutions
ringing out into oblivion there is not a
strong progression to it but i guess
that's not really the point mostly seems
like something to soak in while the
androids listening to this project are
downloading a firmware update now part
of me in concept admires the [ __ ] out of
this song especially as a closer but is
it a track that like i enjoy enjoy as i
listen to the record like is my mouth
watering waiting for this you know
several hour ambient experience to queue
up no
not really but i will say this pretty
much every time i've listened to this
record so far i did find myself
drifting off mentally a little bit
toward the very end during the explosive
finish of mandy and ended up
transitioning into this ambient outro
without fully being conscious of it then
i'm just pretty much feeling it without
really thinking about what i'm listening
to and i may get like 10 or 20 at one
point almost like 30 minutes into it and
then start to think oh uh like when's
when's the next track starting on this
thing i mean this is feeling pretty good
right now but which i think it's a
testament to this album's ability to
genuinely straddle the border between
ambient music and pop music for me to
get like that deep into such an outro
without even really feeling like uh the
progression or the vibe of the record
has been thrown off in a way so yeah on
this project there are some tracks that
i'm not crazy about but it is still a
very unique incredibly interesting lp
with lots of highlights and essentially
sounds like the innermost thoughts
creeping through the minds of an
increasingly isolated generation of kids
raised entirely on the internet feeling
a strong six to a light seven on this
one transition have you given this album
